<a name="backstory"></a>
<h2>Backstory</h2>
<p>
  Orpheus is a small mobile mining colony. The people there earn their livelihood by doing something few are capable of: mining in small, remote, and dangerous areas of space. Their mobile unit is able to go just about anywhere, plunder the goods, and move on to their next assignment so even small ore deposits can turn a healthy profit.
</p>
<p>
  Being so successful, they have some of the best tech and systems that money can buy, and they've also been able to recruit a number of well-trained <a href="#heroes">specialists</a> to protect them in their travels.
</p>
<p>
  Lately they've been reaching out to unexplored areas of the universe hopping along asteroid belts and planetary moons looking for a big score. Today they found it. Unfortunately a <a href="#leviathan">rogue zerg</a> is hot on their ass and its mission is simple: consume and spread. It's eating up this asteroid fast and popping out an assortment of zerg so nasty they'll make your head spin.
</p>
<p>
  I think its time to put these defenses to the test and see if this outfit really is the best in all the stars.
</p>

<a name="gameplay"></a>
<h2>Gameplay</h2>
<p>
  Orpheus is a Hero Defense style game. At the start, you will pick a <a href="#heroes">hero</a> to play as. Using this hero, you will defend the mining colony until they've gathered all of the available resources and safely gotten away.
</p>
<p>
  The mining colony will provide the heroes with experience based on how much they've mined. They will also provide turrets and other defenses to assist the heroes.
</p>
<p>
  The zerg will spawn units randomly with the intent of getting progressively stronger. You might start off facing down just a dozen zerglings or a handful of mutalisks but it won't be long before the entire swarm is beating down your door.
</p>
<p>
  Every minute for 20 minutes, the game will choose a new wave to start creating or it may evolve an existing wave. Initially the game may choose between simpler waves, like spawning 5 zerglings every 10 seconds or spawning 2 banelings every 5 seconds. As the game progresses, more challenging waves and evolutions will be possible. Once a wave has started spawning, it will continue to do so until the final boss has been defeated.
</p>
<p>
  Periodically, a new zerg mutation will be learned. Unlike in the campaign, a unit may learn all of its mutations.
</p>
<p>
  Halfway through the game, a <a href="#minibosses">mini-boss</a> will spawn. It will have abilities like those found in the campaign, requiring heroes to move out of AoEs and to interrupt channels. There may be numerous mini-bosses created, in which case the game will choose one.
</p>
<p>
  At 20 minutes, the <a href="#leviathan">Leviathan</a> will descend on the base directly while still spawning minions and the players will have to defeat it before it destroys the base in order to achieve victory.
</p>
<p>
  At the 5 minute mark and at the 15 minute mark, a short random event may take place (60-80% chance). This may range from something like lava filling the chasm, requiring the heroes to get on high ground, burrowing/flying enemies attacking the base directly, requiring the heroes to make a hasty retreat to defend it, or nydus worms coming up from the ground, presenting the zerg with a new spawn point until they're destroyed. Events will have a warning to give heroes time to react before it actually happens.
</p>
<p>
  Periodically, the base will research one base upgrade and one unit upgrade to aid in its own defense. The base upgrade may be anything from the Terran campaign, like fortified bunkers or flame turrets. The unit upgrade may be a new unit, like a raven or sentry unit, or an upgrade for an existing unit, such as stim pack.
</p>
